Adamawa State Governor, Ahmadu Fintiri says, that state owned media
houses, Adamawa Broadcasting Corporation and Adamawa Television
Corporation (ATV) Yola, would be transformed to ensure wider and
effective coverage of the state. To this end, Fintiri pledged that before the end of this year, the two
stations would cover effectively the northern part of the state and
beyond. He explained that, it imperative for people who voted them to power to
be adequately informed and educated on the dividends of democracy
government provided for them in line with campaign promises. The promise followed request made by the Emir of Mubi, Alhaji Abubakar
Isa Ahmadu, who led a delegation of stakeholders from northern part of
the state on a solidarity visit. He said his administration will ensure that the booster stations reach
the people of northern part of the state, adding that no amount of
pressure would deter him in that regard. He added that Government remains committed to peace and security in
Mubi Zone and the state as a whole, and reminded them that security is
everybody’s business and sought for people to complement efforts of
government to arrest crime and criminality. Earlier in his remark, the Emir of Mubi lauded the giant strides of
the present administration describing it as carrying everyone along. He also commended government’s development in the areas of security,
health, education, civil service and infrastructure development and
urged the governor to sustain the development. Chairman Mubi-South Local Government Council, Alhaji Jingi Rufai,
appreciated the appointment of 144 people from the area into key
offices under his administration.